FastAPI runs synchronous route handlers in a thread pool (default 40 threads via anyio). If all threads are blocked on slow I/O, the entire application stalls.

```python
# BAD — blocks a thread pool slot for 30 seconds
@app.get("/report")
def generate_report():
    time.sleep(30)  # simulates slow DB query
    return {"done": True}

# GOOD — use async with an async DB driver
@app.get("/report")
async def generate_report():
    await asyncio.sleep(30)
    return {"done": True}

# ALSO BAD — async def with blocking call blocks the event loop
@app.get("/report")
async def generate_report():
    time.sleep(30)  # blocks the entire event loop!
    return {"done": True}
```

The rule is simple: if your handler uses blocking I/O, declare it as `def` (not `async def`) so FastAPI runs it in a thread. If everything is truly async, use `async def`. Never mix blocking calls inside `async def` without wrapping them in `asyncio.to_thread()`. You can increase the thread pool size with `anyio.to_thread.current_default_thread_limiter().total_tokens = 100` at startup.

Django 4.1+ supports async views, but the ORM is still predominantly synchronous. Use `sync_to_async` to call ORM methods from async views without blocking the event loop.

```python
from django.http import JsonResponse
from asgiref.sync import sync_to_async
from .models import Article

# Async view with ORM access
async def article_list(request):
    articles = await sync_to_async(list)(
        Article.objects.filter(published=True).values("id", "title")[:20]
    )
    return JsonResponse({"articles": articles})

# Using the async ORM methods (Django 4.1+)
async def article_detail(request, pk):
    try:
        article = await Article.objects.aget(pk=pk)
    except Article.DoesNotExist:
        return JsonResponse({"error": "not found"}, status=404)
    return JsonResponse({"title": article.title, "body": article.body})
```

Django provides native async ORM methods prefixed with `a`: `aget()`, `acreate()`, `acount()`, `aexists()`, and async iterators via `async for obj in queryset`. Deploy under Uvicorn or Daphne with ASGI. Key pitfall: middleware must also be async-aware; sync middleware wrapping an async view forces a thread context switch on every request.

PEP 544 introduced `Protocol` for structural (duck) typing. A class matches a Protocol if it has the required methods and attributes, with no explicit inheritance needed.

```python
from typing import Protocol, runtime_checkable

@runtime_checkable
class Drawable(Protocol):
    def draw(self, x: int, y: int) -> None: ...
    @property
    def visible(self) -> bool: ...

class Circle:
    visible = True
    def draw(self, x: int, y: int) -> None:
        print(f"Circle at ({x}, {y})")

class Square:
    visible = False
    def draw(self, x: int, y: int) -> None:
        print(f"Square at ({x}, {y})")

def render(items: list[Drawable]) -> None:
    for item in items:
        if item.visible:
            item.draw(0, 0)

render([Circle(), Square()])  # works — both satisfy Drawable
assert isinstance(Circle(), Drawable)  # True at runtime with @runtime_checkable
```

`@runtime_checkable` enables `isinstance()` checks but only verifies method existence, not signatures. Use Protocol when you want to decouple modules — consumers define the interface they need, and any compatible class works without importing a base class. Prefer Protocol over ABC when you do not need to share implementation code.

The Anthropic Python SDK supports tool use (function calling) with structured input schemas. Define tools as JSON Schema, and Claude will return `tool_use` content blocks when it wants to call one.

```python
import anthropic

client = anthropic.Anthropic()

tools = [
    {
        "name": "get_weather",
        "description": "Get current weather for a city",
        "input_schema": {
            "type": "object",
            "properties": {
                "city": {"type": "string", "description": "City name"},
                "units": {"type": "string", "enum": ["celsius", "fahrenheit"]},
            },
            "required": ["city"],
        },
    }
]

response = client.messages.create(
    model="claude-sonnet-4-20250514",
    max_tokens=1024,
    tools=tools,
    messages=[{"role": "user", "content": "What is the weather in Tokyo?"}],
)

for block in response.content:
    if block.type == "tool_use":
        print(f"Tool: {block.name}, Input: {block.input}")
        # Execute the tool, then send result back as tool_result
```

After execution, send a `tool_result` message back to continue the conversation. Set `tool_choice={"type": "tool", "name": "get_weather"}` to force a specific tool, or `{"type": "any"}` to require some tool call.

An agentic tool-use loop sends tool results back to Claude and continues until the model stops requesting tools.

```python
import anthropic

client = anthropic.Anthropic()
TOOL_HANDLERS = {"get_weather": get_weather, "search_db": search_db}

def run_agent(user_message: str, tools: list) -> str:
    messages = [{"role": "user", "content": user_message}]
    while True:
        response = client.messages.create(
            model="claude-sonnet-4-20250514",
            max_tokens=4096,
            tools=tools,
            messages=messages,
        )
        messages.append({"role": "assistant", "content": response.content})
        if response.stop_reason == "end_turn":
            return next(b.text for b in response.content if b.type == "text")
        tool_results = []
        for block in response.content:
            if block.type == "tool_use":
                result = TOOL_HANDLERS[block.name](**block.input)
                tool_results.append({
                    "type": "tool_result",
                    "tool_use_id": block.id,
                    "content": str(result),
                })
        messages.append({"role": "user", "content": tool_results})
```

Critical: the `tool_use_id` in `tool_result` must match the `id` from the `tool_use` block. If a tool errors, set `is_error: True` in the tool_result. Add a max iteration guard to prevent infinite loops.

OpenAI's Chat Completions API supports function calling via the `tools` parameter. The model can request multiple tool calls in a single response.

```python
from openai import OpenAI
import json

client = OpenAI()

tools = [{
    "type": "function",
    "function": {
        "name": "search_products",
        "description": "Search product catalog",
        "parameters": {
            "type": "object",
            "properties": {
                "query": {"type": "string"},
                "max_price": {"type": "number"},
            },
            "required": ["query"],
        },
    },
}]

response = client.chat.completions.create(
    model="gpt-4o",
    messages=[{"role": "user", "content": "Find red shoes under $50 and blue hats"}],
    tools=tools,
    tool_choice="auto",  # or {"type": "function", "function": {"name": "search_products"}}
)

for call in response.choices[0].message.tool_calls or []:
    args = json.loads(call.function.arguments)
    result = search_products(**args)
    # Append tool result with call.id as tool_call_id
```

Parallel tool calls are enabled by default. Set `parallel_tool_calls=False` if your tools have ordering dependencies. Use `tool_choice="required"` to force at least one function call.

Few-shot prompting provides input-output examples so the model learns the desired format and reasoning pattern. For structured extraction, include 2-3 diverse examples.

```python
prompt = """Extract entities from the text. Return JSON with the schema:
{"entities": [{"name": str, "type": "person"|"org"|"location", "context": str}]}

Example 1:
Text: "Tim Cook announced new products at Apple Park in Cupertino."
Output: {"entities": [
  {"name": "Tim Cook", "type": "person", "context": "announced new products"},
  {"name": "Apple Park", "type": "location", "context": "event venue"},
  {"name": "Cupertino", "type": "location", "context": "city of Apple Park"}
]}

Example 2:
Text: "The WHO report was reviewed by Dr. Chen in Geneva."
Output: {"entities": [
  {"name": "WHO", "type": "org", "context": "published report"},
  {"name": "Dr. Chen", "type": "person", "context": "reviewed report"},
  {"name": "Geneva", "type": "location", "context": "review location"}
]}

Now extract from:
Text: "{user_text}"
Output:"""
```

Key principles: examples should cover edge cases (abbreviations, titles, ambiguous names). Place examples before the actual input. Keep examples short but representative. For Claude specifically, use XML tags like `<example>` to clearly delineate examples from instructions.

Stream LLM responses to the client using SSE with FastAPI's `StreamingResponse` and the Anthropic SDK's streaming API.

```python
from fastapi import FastAPI
from fastapi.responses import StreamingResponse
import anthropic
import json

app = FastAPI()
client = anthropic.Anthropic()

async def stream_claude(prompt: str):
    with client.messages.stream(
        model="claude-sonnet-4-20250514",
        max_tokens=2048,
        messages=[{"role": "user", "content": prompt}],
    ) as stream:
        for text in stream.text_stream:
            data = json.dumps({"text": text})
            yield f"data: {data}\n\n"
    yield "data: [DONE]\n\n"

@app.get("/stream")
async def stream_endpoint(prompt: str):
    return StreamingResponse(
        stream_claude(prompt),
        media_type="text/event-stream",
        headers={
            "Cache-Control": "no-cache",
            "Connection": "keep-alive",
            "X-Accel-Buffering": "no",  # disable nginx buffering
        },
    )
```

Client-side consumption:
```javascript
const source = new EventSource('/stream?prompt=Hello');
source.onmessage = (e) => {
  if (e.data === '[DONE]') { source.close(); return; }
  const { text } = JSON.parse(e.data);
  document.getElementById('output').textContent += text;
};
```

Set `X-Accel-Buffering: no` header to prevent nginx/reverse proxies from buffering the stream.

The Model Context Protocol (MCP) lets you expose tools, resources, and prompts to LLM clients like Claude Desktop. Use the `mcp` Python SDK to build a server.

```python
from mcp.server.fastmcp import FastMCP

mcp = FastMCP("my-tools")

@mcp.tool()
def search_docs(query: str, limit: int = 5) -> str:
    """Search the documentation database for relevant articles."""
    results = db.search(query, limit=limit)
    return "\n".join(f"- {r.title}: {r.summary}" for r in results)

@mcp.tool()
async def run_query(sql: str) -> str:
    """Execute a read-only SQL query against the analytics database."""
    if not sql.strip().upper().startswith("SELECT"):
        return "Error: Only SELECT queries are allowed"
    rows = await db.fetch(sql)
    return json.dumps(rows, default=str)

@mcp.resource("config://app")
def get_app_config() -> str:
    """Current application configuration."""
    return json.dumps(config.to_dict())

if __name__ == "__main__":
    mcp.run(transport="stdio")  # or "sse" for HTTP
```

Configure in Claude Desktop's `claude_desktop_config.json`:
```json
{"mcpServers": {"my-tools": {"command": "uv", "args": ["run", "server.py"]}}}
```

Tool docstrings become the tool descriptions sent to the model. Type annotations are converted to JSON Schema automatically. The `FastMCP` class handles the JSON-RPC protocol, capability negotiation, and message framing.

When running an MCP server with stdio transport, any output to stdout that is not valid JSON-RPC will crash the connection. This is the most common source of MCP server failures.

```
Error: Parse error - unexpected token 'D' at position 0
```

This happens because `print()` statements, logging to stdout, or library warnings corrupt the JSON-RPC stream.

```python
# BAD — print goes to stdout, corrupts the protocol
@mcp.tool()
def my_tool(query: str) -> str:
    print(f"Searching for: {query}")  # breaks everything
    return search(query)

# GOOD — log to stderr instead
import sys

@mcp.tool()
def my_tool(query: str) -> str:
    print(f"Searching for: {query}", file=sys.stderr)
    return search(query)

# BEST — use Python logging configured for stderr
import logging
logging.basicConfig(stream=sys.stderr, level=logging.DEBUG)
logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)

@mcp.tool()
def my_tool(query: str) -> str:
    logger.info(f"Searching for: {query}")
    return search(query)
```

Another common issue: forgetting to handle exceptions in tools. Unhandled exceptions cause the MCP server process to exit. Always wrap tool implementations in try/except and return error strings rather than raising.

Tailwind supports dark mode via the `dark:` variant. Use the `class` strategy for manual toggling or `media` for automatic OS preference.

```javascript
// tailwind.config.js
module.exports = {
  darkMode: 'class', // or 'media' for OS preference only
}
```

```html
<!-- Components use dark: prefix -->
<div class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">
  <h2 class="text-xl font-bold">Title</h2>
  <p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Subtitle</p>
  <button class="bg-blue-600 dark:bg-blue-500 hover:bg-blue-700
                 dark:hover:bg-blue-400 text-white px-4 py-2 rounded">
    Action
  </button>
</div>
```

```javascript
// Toggle with system preference detection and localStorage override
function initTheme() {
  const stored = localStorage.getItem('theme');
  if (stored === 'dark' || (!stored && window.matchMedia('(prefers-color-scheme: dark)').matches)) {
    document.documentElement.classList.add('dark');
  }
}

function toggleTheme() {
  const isDark = document.documentElement.classList.toggle('dark');
  localStorage.setItem('theme', isDark ? 'dark' : 'light');
}
```

Put the `initTheme()` call in `<head>` as a blocking script to prevent flash of wrong theme (FOWT). With `class` strategy, add `dark` to the `<html>` element, not `<body>`.

When using Tailwind's `class` dark mode strategy with Next.js or Nuxt, users see a flash of the light theme before JavaScript hydrates and applies the dark class.

```html
<!-- BAD: theme script in component — runs after hydration -->
<script>
  // Too late! Page already rendered in light mode
  if (localStorage.theme === 'dark') document.documentElement.classList.add('dark');
</script>
```

The fix: inject a blocking script in `<head>` that runs before any rendering.

```html
<!-- In Next.js: app/layout.tsx -->
<head>
  <script dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: `
    try {
      if (localStorage.theme === 'dark' ||
          (!('theme' in localStorage) &&
           window.matchMedia('(prefers-color-scheme: dark)').matches)) {
        document.documentElement.classList.add('dark')
      } else {
        document.documentElement.classList.remove('dark')
      }
    } catch (_) {}
  `}} />
</head>
```

This runs synchronously before the browser paints, preventing the flash. The `try/catch` handles environments where `localStorage` is unavailable (private browsing in some browsers, SSR). For Nuxt, use the `useHead` composable with `tagPosition: 'head'`.

CSS container queries let elements respond to their parent container's size rather than the viewport. This enables truly reusable components.

```css
/* Define a containment context */
.card-container {
  container-type: inline-size;
  container-name: card;
}

/* Style based on container width */
@container card (min-width: 400px) {
  .card {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 200px 1fr;
    gap: 1rem;
  }
}

@container card (min-width: 700px) {
  .card {
    grid-template-columns: 250px 1fr 150px;
  }
  .card__actions {
    flex-direction: column;
  }
}

/* Container query units */
.card__title {
  font-size: clamp(1rem, 3cqi, 1.5rem); /* cqi = 1% of container inline size */
}
```

```html
<div class="card-container">
  <article class="card">
    <img class="card__image" src="..." />
    <div class="card__body">
      <h2 class="card__title">Responsive to parent</h2>
    </div>
  </article>
</div>
```

`container-type: inline-size` enables width-based queries. Container query units: `cqw` (width), `cqh` (height), `cqi` (inline), `cqb` (block). Browser support: all modern browsers since February 2023. No polyfill needed for new projects.

Framer Motion's `AnimatePresence` enables exit animations when components unmount — something CSS alone cannot handle.

```tsx
import { motion, AnimatePresence } from 'framer-motion';
import { useState } from 'react';

function Notifications({ items }: { items: Notification[] }) {
  return (
    <AnimatePresence mode="popLayout">
      {items.map((item) => (
        <motion.div
          key={item.id}
          initial={{ opacity: 0, y: -20, scale: 0.95 }}
          animate={{ opacity: 1, y: 0, scale: 1 }}
          exit={{ opacity: 0, x: 100, scale: 0.95 }}
          transition={{ type: "spring", stiffness: 300, damping: 25 }}
          layout
          className="bg-white p-4 rounded-lg shadow mb-2"
        >
          {item.message}
        </motion.div>
      ))}
    </AnimatePresence>
  );
}
```

Key props: `mode="popLayout"` removes items from layout flow immediately so remaining items animate smoothly. The `layout` prop animates position changes when siblings are added/removed. Use `mode="wait"` if only one child should show at a time (page transitions). The `key` prop is critical — AnimatePresence tracks children by key to know when one has been removed and should play its exit animation.

Define animation variants as objects for reusable, orchestrated animations. Use `staggerChildren` to cascade animations through a list.

```tsx
import { motion } from 'framer-motion';

const container = {
  hidden: { opacity: 0 },
  show: {
    opacity: 1,
    transition: {
      staggerChildren: 0.08,
      delayChildren: 0.1,
    },
  },
};

const item = {
  hidden: { opacity: 0, y: 20 },
  show: {
    opacity: 1,
    y: 0,
    transition: { type: 'spring', stiffness: 300, damping: 24 },
  },
};

function FeatureGrid({ features }: { features: Feature[] }) {
  return (
    <motion.ul
      variants={container}
      initial="hidden"
      animate="show"
      className="grid grid-cols-3 gap-4"
    >
      {features.map((f) => (
        <motion.li key={f.id} variants={item} className="p-6 rounded-xl bg-white shadow">
          <h3>{f.title}</h3>
          <p>{f.description}</p>
        </motion.li>
      ))}
    </motion.ul>
  );
}
```

Variant labels propagate down the component tree — children automatically inherit `initial` and `animate` from parents. You only need to define `variants` on children; the orchestration (`staggerChildren`, `delayChildren`) is defined on the parent's transition. This pattern works well with `whileInView` for scroll-triggered reveals.

Python 3.12 introduced a new syntax for type parameters that replaces the verbose `TypeVar` declarations.

```python
# OLD (pre-3.12)
from typing import TypeVar, Generic

T = TypeVar("T")
K = TypeVar("K", bound=str)

class Stack(Generic[T]):
    def __init__(self) -> None:
        self._items: list[T] = []
    def push(self, item: T) -> None:
        self._items.append(item)
    def pop(self) -> T:
        return self._items.pop()

def first(items: list[T]) -> T:
    return items[0]

# NEW (3.12+)
class Stack[T]:
    def __init__(self) -> None:
        self._items: list[T] = []
    def push(self, item: T) -> None:
        self._items.append(item)
    def pop(self) -> T:
        return self._items.pop()

def first[T](items: list[T]) -> T:
    return items[0]

# Bounded and constrained
def find_key[K: str](mapping: dict[K, object], value: object) -> K: ...
def encode[S: (str, bytes)](data: S) -> S: ...

# Type aliases (PEP 695)
type Vector[T] = list[T]
type Matrix[T] = list[Vector[T]]
type JSONValue = str | int | float | bool | None | list['JSONValue'] | dict[str, 'JSONValue']
```

The new syntax is more readable and scopes type parameters to the class/function. The `type` statement also supports recursive type aliases without forward references.

Python 3.10+ dataclasses support `slots=True` for memory savings and faster attribute access, and `frozen=True` for immutability.

```python
from dataclasses import dataclass, field
from typing import Self

@dataclass(frozen=True, slots=True)
class Point:
    x: float
    y: float

    def distance_to(self, other: Self) -> float:
        return ((self.x - other.x) ** 2 + (self.y - other.y) ** 2) ** 0.5

    def translate(self, dx: float, dy: float) -> Self:
        # Cannot mutate — return new instance
        return Point(self.x + dx, self.y + dy)

@dataclass(frozen=True, slots=True)
class LineSegment:
    start: Point
    end: Point
    metadata: dict = field(default_factory=dict)

    @property
    def length(self) -> float:
        return self.start.distance_to(self.end)

p1 = Point(0, 0)
p2 = Point(3, 4)
line = LineSegment(p1, p2)
print(line.length)  # 5.0
p1.x = 10  # FrozenInstanceError!
```

`slots=True` (3.10+) generates `__slots__` automatically, reducing memory by ~30-40% and preventing accidental attribute creation. `frozen=True` makes instances hashable (usable as dict keys and set members). Gotcha: `frozen` dataclasses with mutable default fields (like `dict`) are not truly immutable — the dict contents can still be modified.

The `layoutId` prop in Framer Motion creates shared layout animations — an element smoothly transitions between positions when its component tree changes.

```tsx
import { motion, AnimatePresence } from 'framer-motion';
import { useState } from 'react';

function ImageGallery({ images }: { images: ImageItem[] }) {
  const [selected, setSelected] = useState<string | null>(null);

  return (
    <>
      <div className="grid grid-cols-3 gap-2">
        {images.map((img) => (
          <motion.div
            key={img.id}
            layoutId={`image-${img.id}`}
            onClick={() => setSelected(img.id)}
            className="cursor-pointer rounded-lg overflow-hidden"
          >
            <img src={img.src} className="w-full h-40 object-cover" />
          </motion.div>
        ))}
      </div>

      <AnimatePresence>
        {selected && (
          <motion.div
            className="fixed inset-0 z-50 flex items-center justify-center bg-black/50"
            initial={{ opacity: 0 }}
            animate={{ opacity: 1 }}
            exit={{ opacity: 0 }}
            onClick={() => setSelected(null)}
          >
            <motion.div layoutId={`image-${selected}`} className="w-3/4 rounded-xl overflow-hidden">
              <img src={images.find(i => i.id === selected)!.src} className="w-full" />
            </motion.div>
          </motion.div>
        )}
      </AnimatePresence>
    </>
  );
}
```

The browser animates position, size, and border-radius automatically between the grid thumbnail and the expanded modal. Use `layout="position"` to only animate position without size changes.

Class Variance Authority (cva) provides type-safe variant management for Tailwind components, replacing messy conditional class concatenation.

```typescript
import { cva, type VariantProps } from 'class-variance-authority';
import { cn } from '@/lib/utils'; // clsx + tailwind-merge

const button = cva(
  'inline-flex items-center justify-center rounded-md font-medium transition-colors focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 disabled:pointer-events-none disabled:opacity-50',
  {
    variants: {
      variant: {
        default: 'bg-blue-600 text-white hover:bg-blue-700 dark:bg-blue-500',
        destructive: 'bg-red-600 text-white hover:bg-red-700',
        outline: 'border border-gray-300 bg-transparent hover:bg-gray-100 dark:border-gray-600',
        ghost: 'hover:bg-gray-100 dark:hover:bg-gray-800',
      },
      size: {
        sm: 'h-8 px-3 text-sm',
        md: 'h-10 px-4 text-sm',
        lg: 'h-12 px-6 text-base',
      },
    },
    defaultVariants: { variant: 'default', size: 'md' },
  }
);

type ButtonProps = React.ButtonHTMLAttributes<HTMLButtonElement> &
  VariantProps<typeof button>;

function Button({ variant, size, className, ...props }: ButtonProps) {
  return <button className={cn(button({ variant, size }), className)} {...props} />;
}
```

cva generates the class string based on variant selections. `cn()` (clsx + tailwind-merge) deduplicates conflicting utilities so custom `className` overrides work correctly. This pattern is used by shadcn/ui.
